{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-blog-post-js","path":"/inheritance/","webpackCompilationHash":"73be459192e94da462fb","result":{"data":{"site":{"siteMetadata":{"title":"Insights","author":"Dmitry Snisarenko"}},"markdownRemark":{"id":"757a4ba2-f4b7-5e27-9c41-af9eb9fbb46a","excerpt":"GoF stated this over two decades ago. Some\nwarmly accepted languages (Go, Rust) refused of inheritance at all. But it seems\nmany developers haven’t gotten the…","html":"<blockquote class=\"blockquote text-right\">\n  <p class=\"mb-0\">Favor object composition over class inheritance.</p>\n  <footer class=\"blockquote-footer\">Gang of Four in <cite title=\"Design Patterns: Elements of Reusable Object-Oriented Software\">Design Patterns: Elements of Reusable Object-Oriented Software</cite></footer>\n</blockquote>\n<p><a href=\"http://wiki.c2.com/?GangOfFour\">GoF</a> stated this over two decades ago. Some\nwarmly accepted languages (Go, Rust) refused of inheritance at all. But it seems\nmany developers haven’t gotten the problem and still do inheritance to share\ncode between classes. The code looks advanced at first glance. But evolves into\na chimera in no time.</p>\n<p>The code’s design intends is to be future proof and flexible. Ready for\nunpredictable changes. And inheritance in combination with changing business\nrequirements stands on the way of the perfect system based on our\nperfectly-crafted <code class=\"language-text\">BaseSolver</code> class.</p>\n<p>Here is the diagram showing the beginning of disaster:</p>\n<figure class=\"figure\">\n    <span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\" style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 590px;\">\n      <a class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\" href=\"/blog/static/d9c52649c9f4bdb301ed039d26b47be5/6095e/base-class.png\" style=\"display: block\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">\n    <span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\" style=\"padding-bottom: 43.206951026856245%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url(&apos;data:image/png;base64,&apos;); background-size: cover; display: block;\"></span>\n  <img class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\" alt=\"The class diagram showing keeping common methods in Base class\" title=\"The class diagram showing keeping common methods in Base class\" src=\"/blog/static/d9c52649c9f4bdb301ed039d26b47be5/b9e4f/base-class.png\" srcset=\"/blog/static/d9c52649c9f4bdb301ed039d26b47be5/cf440/base-class.png 148w,\n/blog/static/d9c52649c9f4bdb301ed039d26b47be5/d2d38/base-class.png 295w,\n/blog/static/d9c52649c9f4bdb301ed039d26b47be5/b9e4f/base-class.png 590w,\n/blog/static/d9c52649c9f4bdb301ed039d26b47be5/f9b6a/base-class.png 885w,\n/blog/static/d9c52649c9f4bdb301ed039d26b47be5/2d849/base-class.png 1180w,\n/blog/static/d9c52649c9f4bdb301ed039d26b47be5/6095e/base-class.png 1266w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\" loading=\"lazy\">\n  </a>\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class=\"figure-caption text-center\">Figure 1. Sharing common methods in the base class.</figcaption>\n</figure>\n<p>It looks good and nice: 2 instances. Similar in essence. Different in\nimplementation. Share some base class’ methods.</p>\n<p>The other day business decides to add the 3rd instance. And it needs only half\nof our <code class=\"language-text\">BaseSolver</code>’s methods. “No problem,” we say and create another\n<code class=\"language-text\">VeryBaseSolver</code> with only half of the methods implemented:</p>\n<figure class=\"figure\">\n    <span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\" style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 590px;\">\n      <a class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\" href=\"/blog/static/2895b261954acf198a77fc7cb05d3c80/08e2b/very-base-class.png\" style=\"display: block\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">\n    <span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\" style=\"padding-bottom: 43.22943280531426%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url(&apos;data:image/png;base64,&apos;); background-size: cover; display: block;\"></span>\n  <img class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\" alt=\"The class diagram showing creating VeryBase class out of the necessity to borrow couple of methods from Base class\" title=\"The class diagram showing creating VeryBase class out of the necessity to borrow couple of methods from Base class\" src=\"/blog/static/2895b261954acf198a77fc7cb05d3c80/b9e4f/very-base-class.png\" srcset=\"/blog/static/2895b261954acf198a77fc7cb05d3c80/cf440/very-base-class.png 148w,\n/blog/static/2895b261954acf198a77fc7cb05d3c80/d2d38/very-base-class.png 295w,\n/blog/static/2895b261954acf198a77fc7cb05d3c80/b9e4f/very-base-class.png 590w,\n/blog/static/2895b261954acf198a77fc7cb05d3c80/f9b6a/very-base-class.png 885w,\n/blog/static/2895b261954acf198a77fc7cb05d3c80/2d849/very-base-class.png 1180w,\n/blog/static/2895b261954acf198a77fc7cb05d3c80/08e2b/very-base-class.png 1957w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\" loading=\"lazy\">\n  </a>\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class=\"figure-caption text-center\">Figure 2. Establishing a new base class.</figcaption>\n</figure>\n<p>But something smells in this design. It doesn’t look that good anymore. Things\nget worse as soon as business needs a <code class=\"language-text\">ConcreteSolver4</code> with <code class=\"language-text\">method1</code> and\n<code class=\"language-text\">method2</code>. There are multiple ways of providing this but none of them are\nsemantically correct.</p>","frontmatter":{"title":"On class inheritance","date":"January 03, 2019","description":null}}},"pageContext":{"isCreatedByStatefulCreatePages":false,"slug":"/inheritance/","previous":{"fields":{"slug":"/a-better-way-of-displaying-local-loader-in-angular-application/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"A better way of displaying local loader in Angular application"}},"next":{"fields":{"slug":"/react-event-handler-parameter/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"An alternative way of passing parameter into event handler in React"}}}}}